His economic advisors were described by Tim Worstall in https://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2016/03/11/mcdonnells-interestingly-austere-labour-fiscal-policy-spend-and-borrow-more/#3d36136c77a3    as follows... The problem is his little list of economic adviser... David Blanchflower (neverendingly wrong when advising the Bank of England), Mariana Mazzucato (the state is the fount of all technological advance therefore the government should own half of Apple), Anastasia Nesvetailova (who?), Ann Pettifor (out in the wilder reaches of Modern Monetary Theory, government faces no budget constraints at all, it can just keep printing money forever), Thomas Piketty (a microeconomist), Joe Stiglitz (there for the name alone) and Simon Wren Lewis (reasonable actually). I might be being a bit unkind in my descriptions of their views but not all that inaccurate. And then of course there's the egregious Richard Murphy lurking in the background (described in one of this morning's papers as Corbyn's "economic general").

