<data key="bio &amp; notes">Attended Aug 2014 pro-FARC activist mtg in Westminster with (nearly) all Sinn Fein/IRA (of which he is a keen supporter) who all came over to Westminster, strangely enough, for this meeting. of the IRA.   Corbyn was famously part of campaigns to release IRA prisoners known as the Birmingham Six (with Harry Fletcher) and has spoken at IRA men's memorials, leaving no doubt he supported them: no one speaks at a person's memorial unless they support what they did in life.   He has supported the IRA/Sinn Fein since, notably working for "London Labour Briefing" - a hard-left magazine which celebrated the Brighton bomb and joked about the death of Conservative MPs, praising the bomb designed to kill Margaret Thatcher in an article that read: "The British only sit up and take notice [of Ireland] when they are bombed into it" and "What do you call four dead Tories? A start". 
See strong article in the Sun 22 May 2017 attacking Corbyn's anti-British stance all through his life
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/3624310/jeremy-corbyn-is-the-worst-hypocrite-in-modern-uk-politics-he-poses-as-a-caring-man-of-peace-after-career-dominated-by-links-to-murderous-extremists/  Useful article on Corbyn's allies,  http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11820890/The-five-pillars-of-Jeremy-Corbyns-bid-to-run-Britain.html   He was/is close to David Nellist. See a photo of DN and JBC together.   Dump. Labour's plan... Close down the railways until train drivers get a 28% increase on their £47k a year... complain that rolling stock is too old and the railway infrastructure is out of date, and then protest that fare prices are being increased by 3.8%,     
However, his radical socialism might not be as radical as he would like his supporters to believe. See this critical article in the World Socialist Web Site weaknesses in his Socialism which he can be rightly taunted with. https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2016/11/15/reso-n15.html  in which he and other postmodernists are described as nothing more than pseudo-left petty-bourgeoisie. According to them, another hard left group, "Corbyn is supported by the Stalinist Communist Party and the pseudo-left groups, with which he has extensive relations stretching back over decades."     Interesting article describing how Corbyn was propelled to take over the Labour Party... http://www.businessinsider.fr/uk/momentum-the-inside-story-of-how-jeremy-corbyn-took-control-of-the-labour-party-2016-2/  Corbyn is "a 1980s socialist who knows “The Red Flag” by heart but who declines to sing the national anthem."    Now, after his winning leadership speech to Labour staffers at LP head office in Brewer Green, Corbyn disappeared from Brewer’s Green and now uses only the opposition leader’s office in Norman Shaw. He simply does not show up inside Brewer’s Green, even though that is the Labour HQ, and the place with the staff, resources and infrastructure that officially runs the party. And in contrast to the Brewer's Green offices, LP staffers have no idea who he is seeing or what he is doing.  Corbyn spent years visiting Tony Benn every Sunday at his home in Holland Park, so may have been quite hurt when Hillary Benn publicly divorced from his ideas over the strikes on ISIS in Syria.   

He doesn't seem to keep staff long. Is this because he can't manage them, can't get on with others' ideas, or because his close associates (eg McDonnell, McCluskey, Milne, Parker etc) are weeding out people they don't believe are committed enough to their extreme Marxist ideology?  In 2017, Mike Hatchett, Matt Zarb-Cousin, Laura Parker, Simon Fletcher, Neale Coleman (Head of Policy), Anneliese Midgley (Dep Chief of Staff), and Jayne Fisher were all moved on.   NB Mike Hatchet went to work instead for... David Davis!
