<node id="232">
<data key="label">Pat Sheehan</data>
<data key="role">NI AM Sinn Fein/IRA for Belfast West</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">At Aug 2014 pro-FARC activist mtg in Westminster.

Sheehan comes from Belfast. In 1978 he was convicted of causing an explosion and sentenced to 15 years. In prison at the Maze Prison, he joined the hunger strikers in 1981. He survived 55 days without food and stopped when the hunger strike was officially called off on 3 October. 

He was released in 1987, but was convicted again in 1989 for more bombing offences and sentenced to 24 years. However, thanks to Mr Blair, he was released under the terms of the 1998 Belfast Agreement.

On 7 December 2010, he succeeded Gerry Adams as MLA for Belfast West, Adams having resigned in order to contest the Irish general election, 2011. Sheehan retained the seat for Sinn Féin at the 2011 Assembly election.

Sheehan has provoked anger and controversy by describing the Troubles as "probably quite civilised" and saying the IRA "could have left a 1,000lb car bomb on the Shankill" if it wanted to kill Protestants.[" Pat Sheehan's IRA comments spark outrage". The Belfast Telegraph. The Belfast Telegraph. Retrieved 29 August 2012.]

As at August 2015, and some would say this is really quite remarkable, Sheehan is a Political Member of the Northern Ireland Policing Board. See the list of members retrieved 22 August 2015</data>
