<node id="305">
<data key="label">Katy Clark</data>
<data key="role">MP</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">Labour MP in Scotland till 2015. Strong ally of Corbyn. Now his Political Secretary. At Aug 2014 pro-FARC activist mtg in Westminster. Active for de-reselection of LP MPs. See https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/19/labour-democracy-review-asks-nec-to-agree-more-powers-for-members 

Short bio on her fm 2016.. https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/whos-who-in-team-corbyn/   though she seems to have consolidated her position since. 

Also founding supporter of People's Assembly in 2013. Also member of the Stop the War Coalition.

29 Jun 18, Clark published her paper for Corbyn called, ironically, "Democracy Review", which lays out how the LP under Corbyn will control the election of Local Councillors across Brtain. See this article by former LP MP Tom Harris... https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/06/28/now-corbynites-taking-local-councils-labour-right-wasnt-tough/
He writes, "Clark’s review is an explicit recognition by the Corbynite Left that it needs to extend its stranglehold across the wider party beyond London. It cannot do this while non-Corbynite council leaders are kept in place just because those who elect them know a great deal about the local authority they’re running and have a far greater knowledge of the attributes and weaknesses of the candidates who stand for the position. Such pragmatism smacks of – well, pragmatism. And the New Jerusalem will not be built on pragmatism but on ideological purity." ie sound neo-Marxist principles and does away with a fundamental Burkean principle of Democracy... "The new rules, once they’re adopted – and they will be adopted – will dispense with one of the fundamental Burkean democratic principles: that our elected representatives are representatives, not delegates. The Clark review will mean that in future, local Labour councillors, and leaders of Labour groups on local authorities will owe their primary loyalty not to the communities that elected them, but to a relatively small (in comparison with the wider electorate) cohort of political activists." 

Here is info on Clark's "Democracy Review" in the Labour List site, https://labourlist.org/2017/11/revealed-the-full-contents-of-labours-internal-democracy-review/ 

May 2019, Clark is a London candidate for the Euro Elections. I wonder how many of those voting Labour are aware of her radical Left views and connections with Momentum? </data>
