John McDonnell MP, the Shadow Chancellor; Sarah Mosoetsa (professor of sociology at the National Institute for the Humanities &amp; Social Sciences, Johannesburg); Isabel Monal (editor of the Cuban theoretical journal Marx Ahora); David McLellan (visiting professor of political theory at Goldsmith College, University of London); Ben Fine (professor of economics at the School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London); John O’Neill (professor of political economy at Manchester University); Sitaram Yechury, General Secretary of the Communist Party of India (Marxism); Ann-Kathrin Krug, Rosa Luxemburg Foundation, Berlin; Luo Wendong, deputy editor-in-chief of Social Sciences in China Press, Beijing</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">London University's School of Oriental and Arabic Studies, particularly its Marxist Society 

If one needs any idea of the absurdity of much of student life, glance through this list of student societies at SOAS.. https://soasunion.org/activities/societies/

The SOAS Marxist Society organised a conference celebrating Marx’s work and exploring the significance of Marxism in the world today https://socialhistoryportal.org/news/articles/308939

With speakers including:
John McDonnell MP, the Shadow Chancellor; Sarah Mosoetsa (professor of sociology at the National Institute for the Humanities &amp; Social Sciences, Johannesburg); Isabel Monal (editor of the Cuban theoretical journal Marx Ahora); David McLellan (visiting professor of political theory at Goldsmith College, University of London); Ben Fine (professor of economics at the School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London); John O’Neill (professor of political economy at Manchester University); Sitaram Yechury, General Secretary of the Communist Party of India (Marxism); Ann-Kathrin Krug, Rosa Luxemburg Foundation, Berlin; Luo Wendong, deputy editor-in-chief of Social Sciences in China Press, Beijing

11 Dec 18, Identity politics gone mad... Student leaders at SOAS said a ban controlling what a comedian could say was necessary to preserve the event as a 'safe space' and a place for 'joy, love, and acceptance'.  The comedian refused, he was brought up in the Soviet Union and said the contract was something he could have expected to see there from the USSR days. https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-6484947/Comedian-pulls-university-charity-event-asked-sign-behaviour-contract.html

