<node id="393">
<data key="label">Ian Lavery</data>
<data key="role">MP, LP Chairman</data>
<data key="follow up"/>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">He took over as Chair of the LP from Tom Watson in June 2017. Lavery was thought to have had a good election and was therefore promoted to replace Tom Watson as Labour Party chair. Liked by people on all wings of the party he is seen as a unifying force.

Lavery (born 6 January 1963) is former NUM trade union leader from Northumberland who has been the Member of Parliament (MP) for Wansbeck since the 2010 general election. Born and raised Ashington, Lavery began work in the construction industry after leaving school before becoming a mining apprentice.[1] Noted for being the sole apprentice to refuse to work during the miners' strike of 1984-1985, he gradually rose up the ranks of the (NUM) and was chosen to succeed Arthur Scargill as NUM President in 2002. 

Donations from the NUM of 165,000 GBP raised questions but no further action was taken. 

But there is a question mark over his connections with ARCH in Northumberland and a police investigation which the Chief Constable did not pursue. 
