<node id="430">
<data key="label">COMMUNITY CAMPAIGN UNIT</data>
<data key="role">To encourage activism at local level, to make the Labour Party a "social movement rooted in communities."</data>
<data key="follow up">Follow up Katy Clark's "Democracy Review" paper which lays out how Corbyn's LP will control the selection and deselection of Local LP members. 
see also on this... https://labourlist.org/2017/11/revealed-the-full-contents-of-labours-internal-democracy-review/

Follow up various community activities often reported in the CLPD or by CLPD members eg http://www.grassrootslabour.net/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=314:peter-willsman-reports-from-labours-may-2018-executive&amp;catid=36:nec-reports&amp;Itemid=56

</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">The new community organising unit was announced by Corbyn in Jan 2018 and will work with constituency Labour parties and trade unions to try to help them build alliances beyond the party and to campaign on key local issues,
 see http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-42599895

Corbyn said he hoped an approach of "empowering people" would "further invigorate" his party. He wants to control and win the local battles being fought within Labour because, despite performing better than expected at last year's election, Labour still must attract significant new support across the country to be able to get into government. This Campaign Unit will employ activists to extend Labour Party control locally by gathering all local activism under the new Marxist Labour Party banner. 

See also good article at http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/corbyn-labour-community-campaign-unit-transform-the-labour-party-again-a8149886.html  

eg Laura Pidcock, the left-wing MP for North West Durham, told her Facebook followers that the unit will allow their party to have an impact on people’s lives even while it’s still in opposition. “We need to get rid of this awful, destructive government,” she said, “but we don’t have to wait for that to be effective locally”.  ie the LP will motivate and militate to take over local activism on various issues, all designed to pull down and negate the Tory government. 

A Labour government under Corbyn would bolster the rights of those organisers/activists – unions and civil society groups. While the Conservatives warn this will create chaos, Corbyn plans it make it easier for ordinary people to engage in grassroots politics which, he hopes, will further strengthen the left.  THIS IS CLASSIC COMMUNIST ACTIVISM AT LOCAL LEVEL.

22 Jan 18, Momentum has a hit list of around 50 or more moderate Labour MPs they want to deselect and replace with hard left MPs. With their majority in the NEC now, this is certain to go through. What will those moderate MPs do about this? http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5293373/Purge-Labour-moderates.html 

29 Jun 18, Katy Clark, Corbyn's Political Secretary, published her paper for Corbyn called, ironically, "Democracy Review", which lays out how the LP under Corbyn will control the election of Local Councillors across Brtain. See this article by former LP MP Tom Harris... https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/06/28/now-corbynites-taking-local-councils-labour-right-wasnt-tough/
He writes, "Clark’s review is an explicit recognition by the Corbynite Left that it needs to extend its stranglehold across the wider party beyond London. It cannot do this while non-Corbynite council leaders are kept in place just because those who elect them know a great deal about the local authority they’re running and have a far greater knowledge of the attributes and weaknesses of the candidates who stand for the position. Such pragmatism smacks of – well, pragmatism. And the New Jerusalem will not be built on pragmatism but on ideological purity." ie sound neo-Marxist principles and does away with a fundamental Burkean principle of Democracy... "The new rules, once they’re adopted – and they will be adopted – will dispense with one of the fundamental Burkean democratic principles: that our elected representatives are representatives, not delegates. The Clark review will mean that in future, local Labour councillors, and leaders of Labour groups on local authorities will owe their primary loyalty not to the communities that elected them, but to a relatively small (in comparison with the wider electorate) cohort of political activists." 

Here is info on Clark's "Democracy Review" in the Labour List site, https://labourlist.org/2017/11/revealed-the-full-contents-of-labours-internal-democracy-review/ 
</data>
