<node id="958">
<data key="label">Herbert Marcusa</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">In an essay, Marcusa wrote about "liberating tolerance" and made the case for the abolition of Free Speech by those who would defend the capitalist case, the free market economy and liberal ideas. 
He said these ideas were created and promulgated by the oppressor class to continue their oppression, so therefore only the oppressed should be able to speak out (against them). 
This is one explanation for why activists refuse to engage in dialogue.  They think they are taking the moral high road. They don't see their actions are oppressive, suppressive or antagonistic. </data>
