<node id="825">
<data key="label">TELEVISION</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">Television channels are certainly not leftwing per se. 

However, it has become increasingly clear in recent years that certain elements within the mainstream television media are unquestionably biased towards a presentation which favours the Left. 

And furthermore, there are very very few journalists on the right in TV who can balance this left bias. 

So, Paul Mason, a neo-Marxist postcapitalist (his word, though he is more postmodernist) was Economics Editor of Channel 4 Newsnight. Given Mason's Marxist views on capitalism, this is an extraordinary appointment and speaks volumes about those who appointed him. 

Jon Snow, also Channel 4 News, is also very left wing. 

James Purnell, In February 2013 Purnell left the IPPR in order to rejoin the BBC as its Director of Strategy, on a salary of £295,000;[24] he assumed this position on 20 March.[25] As a senior BBC employee he had to resign his membership of the Labour Party. and September 2016, Purnell was appointed as the BBC's Director of Radio and Education, in succession to Helen Boaden.[27] He took up his new position in late October 
He was accused of faking a publicity photo, which suggests a less than rigorous attitude to news reporting, odd that he is now working at the BBC as Director of Strategy. 
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/1564659/Labour-MPs-admit-plan-to-fake-Purnell-photo.html
https://www.revolvy.com/main/index.php?s=James+Purnell&amp;uid=1575

Aysha Rafaele BBC Doc Producer Corbyn supporter, see her Twitter account defending him in his anti-semitism; her position might be influenced by the fact her family is Punjabi.  
Aysha is producing a "revealing" documentary about Mrs Thatcher for the BBC in 2019, which can therefore be expected to show some bias, given Aysha's views. See article on this production at https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/04/18/bbc-broadcast-revelatory-documentary-series-margaret-thatcher/?li_source=LI&amp;li_medium=li-recommendation-widget

See another article in the Spectator on the same subject, decrying what is clear as day but continues to be "accepted", that the BBC and other News Channels are badly biased to the left. https://www.spectator.co.uk/2013/05/next-up-on-newsnight/ 

Mark Thompson, director-general from 2004 until last year, conceded in a magazine interview in 2010 that the corporation had been guilty of ‘massive’ left-wing bias in the past, though without defining when the past ended. A few months later he admitted that the BBC had been ‘historically rather weak and rather nervous’ in its coverage of immigration and Europe.  

18 June 2019, the BBC's blatant bias against the Tory party, against Brexit and especially against Boris Johnson was laid bare in this travesty of a "debate"... https://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-7160341/STEPHEN-GLOVER-pretence-gone-debate-BBCs-bias-hopelessly-exposed.html
and
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-7157497/Imam-attacked-Boris-saying-words-consequences-leaders-debate.html





