<node id="712">
<data key="label">Czech Communist Republic</data>
<data key="follow up">Follow up links between Corbyn and the Czech agents in the UK. 

Also what exactly Vladimir Derer was doing in his country of origin when he was allegedly a Tour Guide. 

</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">The Communist Party seized complete power after the coup d'etat on February 25, 1948. This event marked the start of the Communist totalitarian regime that lasted until the Velvet Revolution of 1989. A second wave of nationalization took place and 95% of all privately owned companies became the property of the state. There were a number of political trials and executions in the following several years. The economy went steadily down under the socialist regime. Basic human rights were suppressed.

The 1960s were a time of greater political and cultural freedom and changes were made in the Communist Party itself. Alexander Dubček, secretary of the Communist Party, attempted to create a more humane version of socialism, "socialism with a human face", that would guarantee people's basic rights and reduce the amount of political persecution in the country. The changes culminated in the spring of 1968 (known as "Prague Spring") when changes reached the government. The growing political freedoms in Czechoslovakia were seen as a threat by the Soviet Union. On August 21, 1968, five Warsaw Pact member countries invaded Czechoslovakia and Soviet troops continued to occupy the country until 1989.  

See https://www.revolvy.com/topic/Czech%20Socialist%20Republic&amp;item_type=topic and https://www.revolvy.com/topic/Czech%20Socialist%20Republic&amp;item_type=topic

This was the country from which agents were dispatched to London to recruit British people, notably make friends with leftwing MPs. Corbyn met one agent, by his own admission, but "just for a cup of tea."  

It is inconceivable that Corbyn did not know the Czech was an agent or what his purpose was. Ken Livingstone certainly did and everyone else at the time knew what Soviet and Soviet satellite nations' agents were doing in all Western capitals at that time. 

Of course Corbyn &amp; Co supported this communist State because he liked its politics: Unitary Marxist-Leninist one-party socialist state (1960–69) and Federal Marxist-Leninist one-party socialist state (1969–89).

See also article in the Sun on Labour MPs who had dealings with communist agents https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/5603634/john-mcdonnell-and-ken-livingstone-among-15-labour-politicians-who-sold-information-to-the-communists-during-the-cold-war-claims-ex-spy/ 

Aside from all of this, the man who had great influence on Corbyn, McDonnell and Lansman (according to Lansman) was the Czech Vladimir Derer. Derer was a "holiday guide" for visitors to the Czech Republic during its communist period which would have been impossible to do without the full support of the State security apparatus, as it would have had full knowledge of any such connections with the West during that time. </data>
