<node id="812">
<data key="label">POSTMODERN NEO-MARXISM THRU AMERICAN UNIVERSITIES</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">The ideas of Derrida and Foucault spread first to the States, to Yale (according to Jordan B Petersen see https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wLoG9zBvvLQ which is well worth listening to all through) and also to John Hopkins University. 

From there it came back to Europe, to the UK. Harvey taught at Oxford in the 1980s. So the influence of US universities is important. 

See also Jean-Francois Lyotard, recently deceased, French philosopher, most famous for defining postmodernism as an incredulity towards metanarratives. check out... https://web.archive.org/web/20071112004504/http://www.california.com:80/~rathbone/lyotard2.htm  

And definitions of postmodernism terms at https://web.archive.org/web/20071114214258/    http://www.california.com:80/~rathbone/local5.htm#paralogy

This is an interesting video of Thomas DiLorenzo, Professor of Economics, talking on behalf of the MISES institute which works against the deconstructive and destructive effects of Cultural Marxism. In the video he explains that destructivism was begun by Marxists even back in the 1930s and earlier https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NG0-WRaS218    which suggests that the French Postmodernists did not come up with anything particularly new but simply adapted what Marxists were already trending towards. </data>
