<node id="818">
<data key="label">Leroy Logan</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">Ex-Superintendent of the Metropolitan Police and former Chairman of the National Black Police Association. Leroy Logan MBE, PhD, BSc 
He retired in 2013 but remains very much active in criticising (the Tory) government and blaming everything on government cuts. 
http://www.nbpa.co.uk/home/leroy-logan-retirement-nbpa-tribute/

In his Twitter string, he retweets a photo of Winnie Mandela describing her as the "mother of Africa" and "her legacy lives on in all our human spirit." Given she was a convicted criminal, involved in murder and other violence, this seems an odd position for a British Policeman to take. 

He also retweeted a tweet from a Irish person which is blatantly pro-IRA and anti-British in which we read, "...British convicts disguised as troops" Also a rather strange attitude to British servicemen by a senior member of the British Police. 

Could it be that Mr Logan is just rather radical leftwing? Certainly writes for the Guardian, always critical of (the Tory) government. 

In 2003, he brought a case against the London Metropolitan Police for racism, in defence against their claim he had fiddled his expenses, and his solicitor was Sadiq Khan who is now London's Mayor. See http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3266581.stm   He was given a large payout, because in a joint statement released by the Met and Mr Logan they both agreed: "This settlement acknowledges that it is not in the public interest to defend the case of racism and victimisation that was put by Chief Inspector Logan."

Logan is quite often asked by the BBC, Sky or C4 to comment on police matters, particularly if they are associated with coloured issues. 
