<node id="893">
<data key="label">Socialist Action</data>
<data key="follow up">John Ross and others who write for this organ.</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">Website for radical Left vigorously pro-Corbyn. 
see http://www.socialistaction.net/category/britain/british-politics/
and http://www.socialistaction.net 

See its views on theory at http://www.socialistaction.net/category/theory/

Socialist Action’s existence came as no surprise to former London Mayor Ken Livingstone. “Almost all of my advisers had been involved in Socialist Action,” Livingstone said. “It was the only rational left-wing group you could engage with. They used to produce my socialist economic policies. It was not a secret group.”

John Ross appears to write many of its articles. He is a British academic.  Ross joined the Trotskyist International Marxist Group (IMG) in the late 1960s. He worked with Bob Pennington to form the IMG Opposition Group. Ross was a central figure in the leadership of the IMG in the early 1980s when it became known as Socialist Action, but he gradually lost the support of much of its membership.  

Ross was leader of one of three groups which emerged from the crisis of this group in the mid-1980s, the one which retained the name Socialist Action. They increasingly ceased to function as a normal left-wing group and became a group of advisors to Ken Livingstone when he was Mayor of London.

To give an idea of its, or other, socialism, Workers Liberty describes Socialist Action as being on the right wing of the Labour Party notwithstanding its main contributor John Ross made his name early on (in the 70s) in the International Marxist Group, see the not very flattering article in Workers Liberty on him at https://search.yahoo.com/search?ei=utf-8&amp;fr=aaplw&amp;p=john+ross+socialist

Simon Fletcher worked for this group at one time, see https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/simon-fletcher-from-communism-to-jeremy-corbyns-consigliere-10508673.html
... this came from the article...

Explaining exactly what Socialist Action is, or was, requires a journey down the byways of the history of Marxism. The group was one of many founded by those who believed that the Bolshevik revolution of 1917 was betrayed by Joseph Stalin, and that his rival Leon Trotsky was international Marxism’s rightful leader. This focus on the existence of Socialist Action could have given Fletcher an uncomfortable time – but with a mayoral election looming, Gordon Brown (who by then was Labour leader) had no intention of getting into an open dispute with Livingstone over whom he employed at City Hall.
</data>
