<node id="921">
<data key="label">Derek Hatton</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">Hatton was leader of the Liverpool city council in the 1980s and leader of Militant Tendency, the extreme radical Left group which tried to infiltrate the Labour Party at that time, much like Momentum has done now. 

Militant was a revolutionary Marxist outfit, a separate party that chose to infiltrate Labour in order to pursue its agenda.
And that agenda was true to its founding principles: to foment revolution, to persuade working class communities that no solution to their ills was to be found through the ballot box, that parliamentary democracy was a myth and only direct action could improve things See piece by Tom Harris, former Labour MP, https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/09/28/return-derek-hatton-signals-labours-slide-back-grotesque-chaos/

22 Sep 18 at the Labour Party conference in Liverpool, Dawn Butler who is Corbyn's Shadow equalities minister, hailed the example of former councillors who set an illegal budget in 1985 in protest at cuts to central government funding. Setting that illegal budget ruined Liverpool and gave Kinnock the chance to evict the Militant Tendency from the Labour Party. https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/09/22/dawn-butler-labour-shadow-equalities-minister-hails-example/

But clearly, Butler isn't so bothered at recommending councils break the law.

Feb 2019, Hatton is formally re-admitted into the Labour Party, notwithstanding his past. Hatton was the ringleader of the Trotskyist Militant tendency in the 1980s which set an illegal budget in Liverpool - causing 'grotesque chaos' in the city - and brought about bitter divisions in the party.  He was thrown out in 1986 but the party's disputes panel is said to have readmitted him last week after he was 'inspired' to return by Jeremy Corbyn's leadership. https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-6718347/Left-wing-Militant-Labour-firebrand-Derek-Hatton-READMITTED.html

 </data>
