<node id="938">
<data key="label">Dr. Michael Derham</data>
<data key="bio &amp; notes">Dr Michael Derham, Northumberland University, Newcastle. 

A keen supporter of Maduro in Venezuela, and an apologist for Hugo Chavez, asked to comment on that country by Sky TV on 26 Jan 2019 when Maduro's opposition has been pushing for new elections. Derham had the neck to blame the US for all Venezuela's financial troubles, which are now showing inflation at a million percent. He claims the US has influenced banks to make trouble for Maduro and that it is this which has created Venezuela's ghastly economic situation, not the communist socialist government of Maduro and his predecessor Chavez. In fact, international analysts assess his presidency has coincided with a decline in Venezuela's socioeconomic status, with crime, inflation, poverty and hunger increasing. 
Chávez aligned himself with the Marxist–Leninist governments of Fidel and then Raúl Castro in Cuba, as well as the socialist governments of Evo Morales (Bolivia), Rafael Correa (Ecuador) and Daniel Ortega (Nicaragua). 
Derham is clearly very anti-America.

This was noticed by another researccher Daniel H. Levine, at the University of Michigan, who was so irritated by Derham's "assessment of Chavez" with which he disagreed, and by his "rereading of Venezuelan history" he wrote a piece entitled Debate Undemocratic Venezuela which appeared in the Bulletin of Latin American Research Vo 22 No 2 pp 231-236, in 2003.   See  https://www.deepdyve.com/lp/wiley/undemocratic-venezuela-ldC5laJXTz


https://www.northumbria.ac.uk/about-us/our-staff/d/michael-derham/</data>
